title: For Sale:  KSG
postcontent: New production unfired direct from the factory Kel Tec KSG 12 shot 12 gauge shot gun. This is serious fire power. The size, shape and design are similar to the currently available Kel-Tec RFB rifle, but the KSG ejects downward, instead of forward. The KSG weighs 6.9lbs and is as compact as legally possible with a 26.1" overall length and an 18.5" cylinder bore barrel. Even with this compact size, the internal dual tube magazines hold an impressive 6 rounds of 12 gage 3" shells each, for a total capacity of 6+6+1 (7 per tube if using 2-3/4" shells). The simple and reliable pump action feeds from either the left or right tube. The feed side is manually selected by a lever located behind the trigger guard. The lever can be positioned in the center detent in order to easily clear the chamber without feeding another round from either magazine. A cross bolt style safety blocks the sear, and the pump release lever is located in front of the trigger guard. The pump includes an under Picatinny rail for the mounting of a forward grip, or a light or laser. The included top Picatinny sight rail will accept many types of optics or iron sights. Forward and rear sling loops are built in, and a basic sling is included.

title: For Sale:  Springfield Model 1870 .50-70 Trapdoor Rifle
postcontent: Springfield Model 1870 Trapdoor Rifle. The Model 1870, of which only 12,000 examples were manufactured between 1870 and 1873, was the precursor to the better known Springfield 1873 45-70 caliber, of which over 700,000 examples were manufactured. The very short service duration and the very small numbers produced, make the Model 1870 very scarce and highly soughet after.The 1870 Springfield was manfactured using a 50-70 caliber muzzle loading barrel from the Civil War, as was the Lock Plate which is date stamped 1863.The rifle is in very good condition and makes a beutiful and unique display. We have had it hanging over the fireplace in our living room (see photo) and almost every visitor has wanted it taken down so they could examine it more carefully. It is 52 inches long and weighs 9 pounds.Trying to determine a fair asking price, I came across another 1870 Trapdoor which was rated in excellent conditeion by New Market Arms, and it sold for $2,200 in 1963. Based on this, I think $1,600 would be a fair asking price, but I will consider reasonable offers.
